<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Simon Creighton, Partner, Bhatt Murphy Solicitors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (LAI 0016)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Prison Law and the scope of legal aid</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This submission is made by Simon Creighton of Bhatt Murphy Solicitors.  I am a partner in the firm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of Bhatt Murphy Solicitors and I have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> specialis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in prison law</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> since 1993</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  I am the co-author of two text books on prison law (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Parole Board Hearings: Law &amp; Practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Prisoners: Law and Practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">).  I have previously given written and oral evidence to the Justice Select Committee on the i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mplications of the IPP sentence. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This submission will address the implications for access to justice of the Government’s proposal to restrict the scope of legal aid for prisoners.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the outset, the Committee’s attention is drawn to the fact that legal aid spend on prisons has actually fallen in the last 2 years and that the increase in overall spend in the last decade was directly related to the increase in the overall prison population but more specifically, to the massive increase in the number of prisoners serving indeterminate sentences following the introduction of the IPP sentence in April 2005.  This sentence has trebled the number of prisoners serving indeterminate sentences.  All of these prisoners have parole hearings (often multiple hearings due to the lack of planning) and many of who experienced significant difficulties with their sentence progression</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The restrictions on the scope of prison law</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Overview</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government’s proposal is to restrict the scope of prison law to just three areas:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Parole Board reviews where the Parole Board has the power to direct release</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Prison disciplinary hearings that engage Article 6</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Matters relating to the calculation of sentences</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals that were published on 5 September 2013 require further clarification as they do not appear to properly relate back to the initial consultation paper.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">particular, the original consultation stated that: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“We anticipate that matters related to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">sentence planning and minimum term review applications</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> would continue to be funded...” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(para 3.18).  However, the proposals set out in the document “Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps” make no reference at all to minimum term review applications and refers to sentence calculation rather than sentence planning.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Minimum term reviews engage Article 6 of the European Convention on Human Rights and so it is not clear why these are out of scope.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sentence calculation is a far narrower category than sentence planning and reviews, relating solely to the accuracy of the prison service’s interpretation of the judicial sentence.  Sentence planning relates to the requirement for all prisoners to have an annual sentence plan that addresses their progress and future targets in custody and so impacts upon their liberty.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further, there remains a lack of clarity about the scope of legal aid provision for parole reviews – this is addressed in more detail below.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overall, the proposals remove from the scope of criminal legal aid all other matters.  Civil legal aid will remain in place in theory, although this will be limited to judicial review applications of unlawful administrative acts and does not cover the parole review process at all.  It will therefore mean that all internal prison law decision making – whether it relates to prison discipline, offending behaviour, access to mother and baby units, resettlement issues, segregation, maintaining contact with the outside world, licence conditions etc... will be outside the scope of criminal legal aid.  In theory, it may be possible for a small number of judicial review applications arising from prison issues to be dealt with under the civil legal aid scheme.  However, civil legal aid is severely restricted in this area and our firm has only 15 matter starts allocated in public law this year and so this does not provide any real alternative.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Parole reviews</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Criminal legal aid has been retained for all parole reviews that engage Article 5(4) and those where the Parole Board has the power to direct release.  This leave out of scope two parole review hearings for people serving indeterminate sentences (ISPs): those referred to the Parole Board by the Secretary of State before the expiry of the minimum term for advice on a move to open conditions and those cases where an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ISP is removed from open conditions and the Secretary of State is seeking advice from the Parole Board on a return to an open prison. This does not correlate precisely to the original consultation which stated that the intention was to retain legal aid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Parole Board review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> matters as these cases concern decisions about ongoing detention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  It should be noted that none of the responses – including the Parole Board’s own response – addressed this issue as there was no warning that any parole proceedings would be out of scope.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Secretary of State is obliged to refer the cases of all ISPs to the Parole Board on the expiry of the minimum term and at intervals of not more than two years thereafter</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  When this referral is made, the Secretary of State specifically requests that if the Parole Board does not direct release, that advice is given on the suitability of the prisoner to move to open conditions.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Secretary of State may also refer ISP cases to the Parole Board solely for advice</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  It has always been the practice to refer the case of ISPs prior to the expiry of the minimum term to obtain advice on the suitability of the prisoner for a move to open conditions. The reason for this is the general policy that ISPs will require a period of time in open conditions where they can be tested in the community before release is granted.  This practice is reflected is a number of documents, most recently in the parole Boar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d’s own guidance to its members which states that the Board </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">regards it as normally ‘essential’ that most indeterminate prisoners spend a period in open conditions”.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, whilst a move to open conditions for an ISP does not engage Article 5(4), it is usually a pre-requisite for release and is therefore clearly intimately connected to ongoing detention. This has been recognised by the courts on numerous occasions</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  It must be noted that the process and procedure for both referrals is identical and that both are governed by the Parole Board Rules 2011. It should also be noted that the practice of holding oral hearings before the Parole Board at this stage was introduced to deal expressly with concerns raised by the Her Majesty’s Inspector of Probation in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Rice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Report</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as this noted that the move to open conditions was the key point where ISPs sentences became focussed on resettlement planning and release.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The failure to allow for legal aid in pre-tariff referrals for ISPs or in cases where ISPs have been moved to an open prison and then removed directly contradicts the original consultation proposal.  It creates a number of anomalies:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Prisoner A and Prisoner B are in the same category C prison.  Prisoner A is pre-tariff and Prisoner B has reached tariff expiry.  Both cases are referred to the Parole Board. Prisoner A will receive no legal aid whereas Prisoner B will be entitled to legal aid and representation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 100.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Prisoner B is moved to open conditions following his hearing.  3 months later, he is removed as the new prison did not feel that the risk assessment was accurate. The case is referred to the Parole Board for further advice. He is now not entitled to legal aid for advice and representation.</span></li></ul><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:56.7pt"><tr style="height:39.75pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:375.65pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case Study A</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">AA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> received a sentence of detention at Her Majesty’s pleasure for a murder committed when she was 15 years old.  She was convicted on the basis of joint enterprise having arranged a meeting that resulted in the fatal confrontation. She has a history of abuse and is traumatised by the events.  The prison service has never conducted a psychological assessment on her.  Through legal advice she has been able to have a detailed psychological assessment prepared that properly identifies her areas of risk and need and a future treatment pathway. This could no longer be carried out. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">She will not be entitled to legal aid to assist her in making an application to have her minimum term reviewed at the half way point.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">She will not be entitled to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">legal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">representation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> before the Parole Board</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> to assess her suitability to move to open conditions before her tariff expires.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are also a number of practical difficulties in relation to prisoners being unrepresented at these hearings:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If there is any sensitive material that cannot be disclosed to the prisoner in person, the Parole Board Rules 2011, rule 8 requires that it is disclosed to a legal representative</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on condition that the prisoner is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not allowed to see it.  If the prisoner is not legally represented, it is difficult to see how rule 8 can function.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When victims attend hearings to deliver impact statements, the prisoner will normally withdraw and the legal representative will remain.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hearings may involve cross examination of witnesses, often on issues relating to risk assessment – it is not appropriate for either the witness or the prisoner if the prisoner has to conduct this cross examination.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 100.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Secretary of State retains the right to be represented creating an inequality of arms</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Other Scope reductions</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All other prison law issues will be out of scope.  This raises very serious concerns about the rule of law in prisons.  Prisoners are in the custody and care of the state and this brings with is positive obligations as well as negative obligations.  </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">It is only viable for individuals to make use of complaints processes if they have</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">free and ready access to the relevant law and policies. </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">Prisoners cannot access advice and assistance – or indeed information – without the active facilitation of the prison authorities. For example, they cannot access the internet, visits a Citizen’s Advice Bureau or see their local councillor or MP. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">No provision has been made for highly vulnerable prisoners, such as children, those who do not speak English or those with learning problems. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:42.55pt"><tr style="height:46.5pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:393.95pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case Study B</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">BB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> was a foreign national who gave birth to a baby with disabilities while on remand.  She spoke no English. After her sentence she was informed that the baby would be removed as they did not know if she would be allowed to remain with her baby when she was eventually returned to Spain.  After taking legal advice it was possible to establish that the Spanish authorities would accept her home to serve her sentence and would allow her to remain with her baby.  The decision was reversed.  This case could no longer be funded under the prison law contact.  Aside from the human costs of an unnecessary separation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> of mother and child</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">, the cost to the public purse would have been enormous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many of the areas removed from scope are precisely those where the active participation of a legal representative helps to promote progress and rehabilitation thereby saving costs and protecting the public.  The example of the manner in which prisoners can access offending behaviour courses is a prime example. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, some of the areas removed from scope directly engage the liberty of the subject.  In relation to category A prisoners the law has required a formal annual review process that mirrors a parole review and contains the possibility of an oral hearing precisely because it has a direct impact on the liberty of the subject</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:40.5pt"><tr style="height:19.5pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:387.75pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case Study C</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">CC</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> had a category A review where he has b</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">en informed that he will remain category A due to security concerns that will not be disclosed to him.  Investigations with the CPS have established that an allegation was made that he had been involved in placing a </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">‘</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">contract</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">’</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> on a prisoner</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> but that they now considered this evidence to be unsubstantiated and unreliable.  Without legal advice, the prisoner would never know the nature of the allegations against him, less still that th</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">y are </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">unreliable</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> All the internal complaints system can produce is a reply that the decision was based on material that will not be disclosed.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">This is obviously highly</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">problematic for prisoners for a wi</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">de variety of reasons.  P</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">risons </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">cannot provide free and ready access to all prisoner service policies.  These are published at the rate of 3 or 4 a month and are generally only available on the internet (which prisoners cannot access). Without access to the information that underpins decisions, a complaints system becomes valueless.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt">Finally, an internal complaints system cannot cope with those situations where the policy itself is wrong. This occurs far more often than one might expect.  For example, the policy on childcare resettlement leave for women with children had to be amended twice within a year for failing to allow for exceptional cases to be considered.  Any applications made through the complaints system simply elicited the response that the decisions had been made in accordance with the policy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Costs Issues</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Finally, the consultation response dismisses the detailed submissions that sought to explain the increase in costs that will actually result from the removal of legal aid</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. For example, the Government rejected suggestions that the removal of legal aid would result in more complaints to the Prisons &amp; Probation Ombudsman (PPO).  The cost of a legal aid case is a fixed fee of £220.  The costs of a PPO investigation are of £830 per case.  Importantly, the response to the Consultation does not set out the cost to the PPO of deciding that a complaint in not eligible for investigation.  In the 2001/2 and 2002/3 Annual Reports, the PPO indicated that a cost of over £100 was incurred simply deciding that a complaint was ineligible. This is vastly more expensive than the associated legal aid costs. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The PPO annual report published on 17.09.2013</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> noted that the overall number of complaints received that year had increased and the number of eligible complaints had increased from 51% to 59%</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  It is noteworthy that the largest single category of complaints is made about property</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and this has been the case every year since property matters were removed from the scope of legal aid.  It is also noteworthy that if one looks back over a decade, that the PPO’s caseload can be directly related to the availability of legal advice and representation.  Thus, in 2001/2002, adjudications comprised 20% of the caseload falling to 9% in 2002/2003</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This fall coincided with the availability of legal representation at disciplinary hearings as a result of the European Court of Human Rights decision in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Ezeh &amp; Conners v UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and amend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ents being laid to the Prison Rules</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The evidence is therefore overwhelming that complaints to the PPO are directly related to the availability of legal advice and that the costs associated with that process are far greater than for resolving matters through legal aid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Finally, in his evidence to the Committee, the Minister accepted that the proposals were not in fact about costs savings but were ideologically driven</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  It is clear that if the reforms are about the public acceptability of providing legal aid, this is not an issue of allocating scarce resources and requires proper scrutiny and accountability as it effectively involves removing the rule of law in its current form from prisons.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">25 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Minimum term review applications are matters that relate to the setting of the tariff for prisoners sentence to life/indeterminate sentences</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Para 3.20 – emphasis as in original</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Crime (Sentences) Act 1997, s 28(7)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Criminal Justice Act 2003, s 239(2)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/offenders/parole-board/icm-manual.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/offenders/parole-board/icm-manual.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Eg: Irwin J in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (Hill) v SSHD</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">[2007] EWHC 2164 (Admin)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">“it seems clear that release from closed conditions with no period in open prison is very rare.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (para 6)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/publications/inspectorate-reports/hmiprobation/anthonyricereport-rps.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/publications/inspectorate-reports/hmiprobation/anthonyricereport-rps.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> A solicitor, barrister, medical practitioner or someone of standing approved by the Board</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Williams v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">[</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2002] EWCA Civ 498 the Court of Appeal were informed that the only 3 category A lifers to ever have been released and th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">se all took place under the Good Friday agreement. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Although it is important to recall that when asked about costs by the Select Committee, the Minister stated that the decision in relation to prisons was ideological not costs driven.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.ppo.gov.uk/docs/ppo-annual-report-2012-13.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ppo.gov.uk/docs/ppo-annual-report-2012-13.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ibid, p 13</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 18% of all complaints and 24% if immigration detention complaints – page 17</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.ppo.gov.uk/docs/annual-report-2002-20031.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ppo.gov.uk/docs/annual-report-2002-20031.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> p 7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn15"></a><a href="#_ftnref15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmjust/91/130703.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmjust/91/130703.htm</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> questions 198-210</span></p></body></html>